2. Gene coding according to fractal genes ? Generally, fractal control mechanisms ?
3. The "growth and development" [biological] design philosophy, based on attraction-repulsion rules / models ?
4. The power law principle ? ("fractilic")
5. Why did the concept of the "optimum / ideal" emerge ?




Sopolsky lecture notes 23. Language:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SIOQgY1tqrU
- 2 generation cells - "radial glial that establish baseline super-structure, 2nd generation being neurons that do random wandering, then wire up into "optimal" nodes (roadways / street networks…)
- "what does it look like ?" (representation, the need to start with representation ?), universality linguistic principles
- semanticity, "bucket [sounds]", categorical placement of "units of sounds" (discretization)
- embedded clauses
- recursion, generativity, combinatorics (complexity [metrics])
- displacement
- arbitrariness (ambiguity), signal-message arbitrariness
- meta-communication (and self-analysis)
- "baby-talk", motherese (and emergent behaviors)
- motoric aspect of language vs cognitive/conceptual aspect of language (system "sensors" (processing) vs cognitive perception processing of sensor data)
- prosody (linguistic subtleties)
- cognitive structures of language
- linguistic modularity, Williams Syndrome, pedigrees
- lateralized linguistic brain functionality (principle of lateralization), WADA test
- motoric regulation, language production ([production] aphasia)
- reinforcement (behaviorist) language learning Skinner - vs Chomskian (singularity / "inflection" point of linguistic generativity)
- innate linguistic structure (generalization from [imperfect, incomplete] instruction / examples)
- poverty of stimulus argument (generative-discriminative nets / GANs… ? Language Recurrent NNs)
- directed teaching of language (and curriculum learning)
- "universality of language sounds"
- peer socialization vs social influences (Judith Rich Harris)
- "inculcation of values of [home] language"
- linguistic diglossia
- kinship, appellation
- external vs internal linguistic landmarks
- Sapir-whorf hypothesis
- linguistic suppression, omission, confabulation, etc…
- linguistic dissemination
- [alternative] mechanisms for language production
- "babbling"
- "enabling"… ?
- "in-continuity of teachers", (and consistency)
- logical progressions, analogy
- semantic category constrained error


Questions
1. The causes for the rises and falls of language ? Formal Theory of computation connections ? Smart / Incomplete [and formal / informal] contracts relations ?
2. Extension of "baseline" linguistics [capabilities] by mathematics, logic, sciences, visual representation, etc… ?
